    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-09-03T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-09-03T18:00:00-05:00" n="651"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d651">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">884.6363 African Exploration and Development
                    Corp./19: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-09-03T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 3, 1935—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>52. The following statement was issued to the press tonight:</p>
                <p>[Here follows the statement quoted in telegram printed <hi rend="italic"
                        >supra.</hi>]</p>
                <p>There follows the statement issued by Mr. Walden in which he reviews the history
                    of the negotiations and concludes with the following paragraphs: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“This matter was handled in the regular course of business as a private
                            transaction with Ethiopia, but without consultation with any other
                            Government.</p>
                        <p>In view of the misleading nature of the news comment in Saturday morning
                            papers, I felt it necessary to give all the facts to our State
                            Department before issuing any public statement. Today I have done this,
                            and after conference with the Secretary of State have decided to advise
                            the Ethiopian Government of our intention to abandon the
                            concession.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>You should seek an immediate audience with the Emperor and apprize him of the
                    foregoing. At the same time you should advise him that the African Exploration
                    and Development Company has informed the Department that the Company will
                    transmit to Addis Ababa as soon as possible formal written notice of its
                    intention to abandon the concession.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
